        "text": "Do you cringe at the thought of sky-high international calling fees? You're not alone. Despite colossal strides in technology that have shrunk our global village, the cost of reaching a friend or loved one internationally can still pack a hefty punch. That is unless you're armed with the right tools, savvy tips, and cost-effective apps to dial abroad.\n\nIn this short guide, we explore the various ways to best call Sri Lanka from the US without breaking the bank. We take you through the basics (e.g. country and exit codes, voice over IP, etc.) before walking you through the best strategies for calling Sri Lanka as affordably and as hassle-free as possible!\n\nSri Lankan Dialling Codes\n\nRemember those mysterious alphanumeric codes that precede every phone number? Dialling codes might seem like relics of a bygone era, but they're still vital in our digital world, helping you to steer your calls to the right country or region. Let's unravel the two main ones:\n\nSri Lanka Country Code\n\nWhen it comes to calling Sri Lanka, you'll need to use Sri Lanka's country code, which is +94. This means you'll need to ensure that all calls you make to Sri Lanka begin with this code. If you're calling via landline, you can enter 01194 instead, which includes the American exit code, 11.\n\nTo see how this works, here's a fictitious example of how a number would look if you're calling Sri Lanka from the US on your cell phone:\n\n+94 1329 5678\n\nAnd here's how the same number should be dialled if you called it via your landline instead:\n\n01194 1329 5678\n\nHow to Call Sri Lanka From the US\n\nWhen it comes to calling Sri Lanka from the US, you'll find a few options at your disposal. Here are the three most popular or affordable ones:\n\nOption 1: Voice Over IP\n\nA popular way to call somebody in Sri Lanka from the US is by using voice over IP (VoIP) calls. This is a type of call where you use an app connected to the internet to call somebody else using the same app. Here are a few of the most well-known and widely-used apps that support VoIP calls to Sri Lanka and elsewhere in the world:\n\nWhatsApp\n\nGoogle Meet\n\nSkype\n\nTelegram\n\nFacebook Messenger\n\nFaceTime\n\nThe advantage of using these platforms is that they're extremely cheap, requiring you and the person you're calling to use the same app and have an internet connection. (It's often said that these calls are free, but this isn't strictly true since there are mobile data or WiFi costs involved, but these are typically quite small.) On the other hand, the disadvantage of calling via VoIP is that neither you nor the person you're calling will necessarily always have an internet connection or even a phone capable of connecting to the internet.\n\nIf you're looking for a way to call someone via a VoIP service and you need to top up their mobile data so they have an internet connection, you can buy some data for them right on our website! Just follow the link below:\n\nOption 2: Directly by Landline or Mobile\n\nYour second option (and, sadly, still a popular one) is to pick up your cell phone or landline and call a number in Sri Lanka directly.\n\nWhile this might sound convenient (and it is), it comes with one big drawback: the cost. You'll generally be charged by the second for making an international call from the USA — even for the ringing at the beginning of the call! Big networks in the USA like AT&T, Verizon, T-Mobile, and others tend to charge exorbitant rates for international calling, so this is a method we generally recommend against unless you're ready to swallow the costs."
